\begin_layout Standard
Los polinomios de Taylor de la función exponencial centrados en 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 son inmediatos pues las derivadas de 
\begin_inset Formula $\e^{x}$
\end_inset

 en 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 valen todas 1.
 Luego 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{n}(\exp,0)(x)=1+\sum_{k=1}^{n}\dfrac{1}{k!}x^{k}
\]

\end_inset

Como 
\begin_inset Formula $\sen\tl(x)=\cos(x)=\sen(\frac{\pi}{2}+x)$
\end_inset

, se sigue que 
\begin_inset Formula $\sen^{(n)}(x)=\sen(\frac{n\pi}{2}+x)$
\end_inset

.
 En particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sen^{(n)}(0)=\sen(\frac{n\pi}{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Por tanto 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{n}(\sen,0)(x)=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\dfrac{\sen(\frac{k\pi}{2})}{k!}x^{k}
\]

\end_inset

Como para 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 par es 
\begin_inset Formula $\sen(\frac{k\pi}{2})=0$
\end_inset

 y para 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 impar 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2q-1$
\end_inset

 es 
\begin_inset Formula $\sen(\frac{(2q-1)\pi}{2})=(-1)^{q+1}$
\end_inset

, resulta que 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{2n-1}(\sen,0)(x)=T_{2n}(\sen,0)(x)=\sum_{k=1}^{n}\dfrac{(-1)^{k+1}}{(2k-1)!}x^{2k-1}
\]

\end_inset

Análogamente para la función coseno 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{2n}(\cos,0)(x)=T_{2n+1}(\cos,0)(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\dfrac{(-1)^{k}}{(2k)!}x^{2k}
\]

\end_inset

Pongamos 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(1+x)^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Tenemos que 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(n)}(x)=\alpha(\alpha-1)(\alpha-2)\cdots(\alpha-n+1)(1+x)^{\alpha-n}$
\end_inset

.
 Por lo que 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{n}(f,0)(x)=1+\sum_{k=1}^{n}\dfrac{\alpha(\alpha-1)(\alpha-2)\cdots(\alpha-k+1)}{k!}x^{k}
\]

\end_inset

Cualquiera sea el 
\emph on
número real
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 y el número natural 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 se define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\binom{\alpha}{k}=\dfrac{\alpha(\alpha-1)(\alpha-2)\cdots(\alpha-k+1)}{k!}
\]

\end_inset

Por convenio 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{\alpha}{0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Con ello podemos escribir 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{n}(f,0)(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\binom{\alpha}{k}x^{k}
\]

\end_inset

Para obtener los polinomios de Taylor de 
\begin_inset Formula $\log(1+x)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\arctg x$
\end_inset

